- learn the basics of module theory: basic structural theory of modules, modules over principal ideal domains;
- learn the basics of representation theory: group representations and group rings, Maschke's theorem, character theory, constructions of representations;
- apply basic results and techniques to solve problems in the theory and other related subjects
- prepare for graduate studies in algebra-related subjects such as algebraic geometry, algebraic number theory and representation theory.

Students are expected to learn the basic optimization theory and concepts with emphasis on their mathematical aspects. Upon completion of the course, students are expected to:

1. learn the basic mathematical concepts and techniques for optimization;
2. be aware of the important role of mathematics in optimization;
3. appreciate the importance of optimization theory in the real world;
4. learn how to design optimization models for real-world problems;
5. implement algorithms/methods in solving problems on optimization.

